english:
  title: Record of the New Construction of the Guest Hall at Taeан County
  author: Nam Su-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Taeан County was once Sotae County in ancient Silla. Its soil is fertile, suited to the five grains, and blessed with the bounty of fish and salt—a land where the people dwelt in contentment. Yet situated upon the coast, it lay exposed to the tide of corsairs who swept these waters. In the waning days of Goryeo, when martial vigilance grew slack and Japanese raiders grew bold, the county suffered grievously in the year Hongwu jianchou. The magistrate, with scarcely two clerks in attendance, sought refuge in Seoisan County, then removed again to Yeysan. Not until the year gengwu did the bandit scourge subside enough to allow his return to Seoisan, where a fortress was erected and named Sundae, to guard against maritime raiders while serving the dual office of magistrate. Yet the scattered people did not return, and the entire region became overgrown with thorns, abandoned to beasts.

    The court established a military training ground there. In the year Yongle bingshan, our King Taejong, while on his spring hunt, beheld this desolate land with sorrow and commanded that the county's ancient seat be restored. The following year, walls were raised. Yet midst these labors of renewal, the public hall remained unfinished. A makeshift chamber of four pillars was hastily erected to receive royal envoys, narrow and exposed to the elements—this imperfect structure endured for more than twenty years.

    In the spring of the second month of the year Zhengton jiwei, my fellow scholar Kim Wanja was appointed magistrate here by virtue of his martial prowess and administrative skill. Swift in counsel, he managed both military affairs and civil matters with ease. Stirred by ambition to restore what lay waste, he consulted with the people and resolved to build a new public hall. The townspeople Li Huai, Li Di, and others responded, contributing funds and labor. With timber sound and tiles of quality, work began.

    They erected a great hall of five sections, three bays deep; flanking chambers of five sections, five bays each; a southern hall of five sections, three bays; eastern and western galleries of five sections, four bays each; and inner chambers of five sections, three bays each. Kitchens, storehouses, and bathing quarters all found their proper place. In total, eighty-three bays rose from the earth. Work commenced in the tenth month of jiwei and concluded in the eighth month of xinyu. The structure stands magnificent, its painted beams bright and fresh—a glory to the county.

    Magistrate Kim sent word requesting that I record these events. As a historian by office, it falls to me to chronicle all works of construction—this is my duty. How much more so when matters touch upon the very course of civilization itself. That this county, having wandered through calamity, should at last enter an age of peace; that it should gain a virtuous magistrate to restore its desolate fields and rebuild its walls; that it should cast off the shameful habit of neglect and raise monuments to order—surely this is cause for the world to rejoice. This deed deserves recording.

    The ancients said: "To find a worthy magistrate for a county is difficult. Having found one, to accomplish great works is more difficult still. Having accomplished them, to find a successor who will not allow them to decay—this is hardest of all." Our county has been fortunate in what few attain. Yet can we know whether those who come after will carry forward Magistrate Kim's vision? This too I must record, as a warning to generations yet unborn.
  footnotes:
    - Nam Su-mun (南秀文) was a 15th-century Joseon scholar and official. He was known for his historical writings and served in various administrative capacities.
    - King Taejong's spring hunt (永樂 bingshan year) marks the early 15th century period of Joseon's consolidation and territorial reorganization.
    - The reference to Zeng Nanfeng (曾南豐) alludes to Zeng Guofan's historical commentary tradition, invoking classical precedent for the importance of virtuous leadership and its lasting legacy.
    - The architectural measurements given (bays and sections) follow traditional East Asian building conventions where 楹 (beams/bays) and 架 (sections) denote structural units.
